Wife and I finally tried Da Claudio late last night a little after 10pm. We were neighborhood fans of Claudio's old restaurant, Barbarini by the seaport that was wrecked by Sandy. This new venture is more ambitious, and he nails it. The concept of having a salumeria as part of the restaurant really lends old world authenticity. That part is the same, but this time he is running a large, very high quality staff with an open kitchen, uniformed chefs, an expert mixologist all in addition to the dedicated, knowledgable "salumeria guy" who creates the excellent cheese and salumi plates that were always the draw for us back at Barbarini. The whole experience is really elevated dining and really on a par with the best Italian places in the city. The pasta dishes we had were VERY strong. Melt in you mouth gnocchi and fresh pesto and olive oil fettucini. For a guide our other favorite places are Osteria Morini and Locanda Verdi and Da Claudio for us in now in the same league despite not having the celebrity backing from afar. Claudio was there last night and we imagine almost around the clock keeping things up to exacting standards. We really hope his vision succeeds for his sake and for the sake of downtown Manhattan. We are really lucky to have someone of this calibre willing to invest this much this far south on the island.

Dropped by the low-key 'soft opening' of Da Claudio last night on Anne St. These are the guys who run 'Cafe Linda' in Midtown (a great lunch) and the ill-fated Barbarini (destroyed during Sandy). Remarkably inventive cocktails (they desiccate their own pomegranates, sumptuous starters and plenty of deli-cheese-meat type stuff that will please your inner-italian (and let's face it who does not like Italian eh?) And one other surprise - much cheaper than your average Tribeca fair! i can't wait for the take out options.
